[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":665},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F21\u002Fjavascript-puzzle-01-evaluate-string-without-eval\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F21\u002Fjavascript-puzzle-01-evaluate-string-without-eval\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F21\u002Fjavascript-puzzle-01-evaluate-string-without-eval\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F21\u002Fjavascript-puzzle-01-evaluate-string-without-eval\u002F":640,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F21\u002Fjavascript-puzzle-01-evaluate-string-without-eval\u002F":649},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20230321\u002F3298342448\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":624,"date":625,"description":626,"extension":627,"lang":628,"meta":629,"navigation":111,"path":630,"readingMinutes":631,"seo":632,"standalone":633,"stem":634,"tags":635,"tldr":637,"updated":625,"url":638,"__hash__":639},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-puzzle-01-evaluate-string-without-eval.md","A JavaScript Puzzle: Compute a Math Expression Without Using eval","1001306638",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":614},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,61,72,76,79,83,89,126,139,145,151,166,197,204,210,215,219,232,325,331,404,408,417,421,428,534,537,555,561,587,590,594,610],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"I came across a pretty fun little puzzle the other day that someone shared, so I figured I'd jot down my thought process as a quick post. Maybe one day I'll come back and read this myself.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"the-puzzle","The puzzle",[17,25,26],{},"Here's the puzzle:",[28,29,34],"pre",{"className":30,"code":31,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","const a = '1 + 2 + 3';\n","js","",[35,36,37],"code",{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,39,42,46,50,53,57],"span",{"class":40,"line":41},"line",1,[38,43,45],{"class":44},"sWyjQ","const",[38,47,49],{"class":48},"sCcAr"," a",[38,51,52],{"class":44}," =",[38,54,56],{"class":55},"sTRMh"," '1 + 2 + 3'",[38,58,60],{"class":59},"sMAXC",";\n",[17,62,63,64,67,68,71],{},"Take the value of ",[35,65,66],{},"a"," above, compute it, and get ",[35,69,70],{},"6"," as the result.",[12,73,75],{"id":74},"working-through-it","Working through it",[17,77,78],{},"Let me walk through how I thought about this one.",[80,81,82],"h3",{"id":82},"eval",[17,84,85,86,88],{},"Let's start with the easiest solution — using ",[35,87,82],{}," to do the math.",[28,90,92],{"className":30,"code":91,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"const a = '1 + 2 + 3';\n\neval(a); \u002F\u002F 6\n",[35,93,94,106,113],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,95,96,98,100,102,104],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,97,45],{"class":44},[38,99,49],{"class":48},[38,101,52],{"class":44},[38,103,56],{"class":55},[38,105,60],{"class":59},[38,107,109],{"class":40,"line":108},2,[38,110,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},true,"\n",[38,114,116,119,122],{"class":40,"line":115},3,[38,117,82],{"class":118},"sj_SG",[38,120,121],{"class":59},"(a); ",[38,123,125],{"class":124},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F 6\n",[17,127,128,129,131,132,138],{},"But generally speaking, ",[35,130,82],{}," is a function you don't want to use. Why? Take a look at how MDN ",[66,133,137],{"href":134,"rel":135},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FWeb\u002FJavaScript\u002FReference\u002FGlobal_Objects\u002Feval",[136],"nofollow","describes it",":",[140,141,142],"blockquote",{},[17,143,144],{},"The eval() function evaluates JavaScript code represented as a string and returns its completion value. The source is parsed as a script.",[17,146,147,148,150],{},"In plain terms, that means ",[35,149,82],{}," takes whatever string you hand it, runs it as actual JavaScript, and gives you back the result.",[17,152,153,154,159,160,162,163,165],{},"Looks super convenient, right? But if your project uses ESLint to manage code style, you'll find that ",[66,155,158],{"href":156,"rel":157},"https:\u002F\u002Feslint.org\u002Fdocs\u002Flatest\u002Frules\u002Fno-eval",[136],"ESLint"," tells you not to use ",[35,161,82],{},", because it opens up security problems. For example, you can use ",[35,164,82],{}," to run malicious code:",[28,167,169],{"className":30,"code":168,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"const a = 'alert(\"是 Ray 不是 Array\")';\n\neval(a); \u002F\u002F pops up an alert showing \"是 Ray 不是 Array\"\n",[35,170,171,184,188],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,172,173,175,177,179,182],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,174,45],{"class":44},[38,176,49],{"class":48},[38,178,52],{"class":44},[38,180,181],{"class":55}," 'alert(\"是 Ray 不是 Array\")'",[38,183,60],{"class":59},[38,185,186],{"class":40,"line":108},[38,187,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},[38,189,190,192,194],{"class":40,"line":115},[38,191,82],{"class":118},[38,193,121],{"class":59},[38,195,196],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F pops up an alert showing \"是 Ray 不是 Array\"\n",[17,198,199],{},[200,201],"img",{"alt":202,"src":203},"Alert popup","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FGPGNVDd.png",[17,205,206,207,209],{},"That's why a lot of puzzles ban ",[35,208,82],{}," outright — and on top of that, MDN itself flags the function as something you shouldn't use:",[140,211,212],{},[17,213,214],{},"Warning: Executing JavaScript from a string is an enormous security risk. It is far too easy for a bad actor to run arbitrary code when you use eval(). See Never use eval()!, below.",[80,216,218],{"id":217},"new-function-or-function","new Function or Function",[17,220,221,222,225,226,229,230,138],{},"At this point you might be thinking — okay, can I use ",[35,223,224],{},"new Function"," or ",[35,227,228],{},"Function"," instead? Both can pull off the same thing. Here's an example with ",[35,231,224],{},[28,233,235],{"className":30,"code":234,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"const a = '1 + 2 + 3';\n\nconst calc = (val) => {\n  return new Function(`return ${val}`)();\n}\n\ncalc(a); \u002F\u002F 6\n",[35,236,237,249,253,278,304,310,315],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,238,239,241,243,245,247],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,240,45],{"class":44},[38,242,49],{"class":48},[38,244,52],{"class":44},[38,246,56],{"class":55},[38,248,60],{"class":59},[38,250,251],{"class":40,"line":108},[38,252,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},[38,254,255,257,260,262,265,269,272,275],{"class":40,"line":115},[38,256,45],{"class":44},[38,258,259],{"class":118}," calc",[38,261,52],{"class":44},[38,263,264],{"class":59}," (",[38,266,268],{"class":267},"s_sBn","val",[38,270,271],{"class":59},") ",[38,273,274],{"class":44},"=>",[38,276,277],{"class":59}," {\n",[38,279,281,284,287,290,293,296,298,301],{"class":40,"line":280},4,[38,282,283],{"class":44},"  return",[38,285,286],{"class":44}," new",[38,288,289],{"class":118}," Function",[38,291,292],{"class":59},"(",[38,294,295],{"class":55},"`return ${",[38,297,268],{"class":59},[38,299,300],{"class":55},"}`",[38,302,303],{"class":59},")();\n",[38,305,307],{"class":40,"line":306},5,[38,308,309],{"class":59},"}\n",[38,311,313],{"class":40,"line":312},6,[38,314,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},[38,316,318,321,323],{"class":40,"line":317},7,[38,319,320],{"class":118},"calc",[38,322,121],{"class":59},[38,324,125],{"class":124},[17,326,327,328,330],{},"The thing is, this approach has the exact same problem as ",[35,329,82],{}," — it's also not recommended, because it carries the same security risks:",[28,332,334],{"className":30,"code":333,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"const a = 'alert(\"是 Ray 不是 Array\")';\n\nconst calc = (val) => {\n  return new Function(`return ${val}`)();\n}\n\ncalc(a); \u002F\u002F pops up an alert showing \"是 Ray 不是 Array\"\n",[35,335,336,348,352,370,388,392,396],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,337,338,340,342,344,346],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,339,45],{"class":44},[38,341,49],{"class":48},[38,343,52],{"class":44},[38,345,181],{"class":55},[38,347,60],{"class":59},[38,349,350],{"class":40,"line":108},[38,351,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},[38,353,354,356,358,360,362,364,366,368],{"class":40,"line":115},[38,355,45],{"class":44},[38,357,259],{"class":118},[38,359,52],{"class":44},[38,361,264],{"class":59},[38,363,268],{"class":267},[38,365,271],{"class":59},[38,367,274],{"class":44},[38,369,277],{"class":59},[38,371,372,374,376,378,380,382,384,386],{"class":40,"line":280},[38,373,283],{"class":44},[38,375,286],{"class":44},[38,377,289],{"class":118},[38,379,292],{"class":59},[38,381,295],{"class":55},[38,383,268],{"class":59},[38,385,300],{"class":55},[38,387,303],{"class":59},[38,389,390],{"class":40,"line":306},[38,391,309],{"class":59},[38,393,394],{"class":40,"line":312},[38,395,112],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":111},[38,397,398,400,402],{"class":40,"line":317},[38,399,320],{"class":118},[38,401,121],{"class":59},[38,403,196],{"class":124},[17,405,406],{},[200,407],{"alt":202,"src":203},[17,409,410,411,413,414,416],{},"So ",[35,412,224],{}," and ",[35,415,228],{}," are off the table too. Which means we need to come up with another way to solve this.",[80,418,420],{"id":419},"array-methods","Array methods",[17,422,423,424,427],{},"This one's a bit more interesting. We'll use the ",[35,425,426],{},"map"," array method to solve it. Let's look at the code first:",[28,429,431],{"className":30,"code":430,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"const a = '1 + 2 + 3';\nconst b = a.split(' + '); \u002F\u002F [ \"1\", \"2\", \"3\" ] — split the string into an array\nconst c = b.map(Number); \u002F\u002F [ 1, 2, 3 ] — convert each item to a number\nconst total = c.reduce((acc, cur) => acc + cur); \u002F\u002F 6 — add them up with reduce\n",[35,432,433,445,471,491],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,434,435,437,439,441,443],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,436,45],{"class":44},[38,438,49],{"class":48},[38,440,52],{"class":44},[38,442,56],{"class":55},[38,444,60],{"class":59},[38,446,447,449,452,454,457,460,462,465,468],{"class":40,"line":108},[38,448,45],{"class":44},[38,450,451],{"class":48}," b",[38,453,52],{"class":44},[38,455,456],{"class":59}," a.",[38,458,459],{"class":118},"split",[38,461,292],{"class":59},[38,463,464],{"class":55},"' + '",[38,466,467],{"class":59},"); ",[38,469,470],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F [ \"1\", \"2\", \"3\" ] — split the string into an array\n",[38,472,473,475,478,480,483,485,488],{"class":40,"line":115},[38,474,45],{"class":44},[38,476,477],{"class":48}," c",[38,479,52],{"class":44},[38,481,482],{"class":59}," b.",[38,484,426],{"class":118},[38,486,487],{"class":59},"(Number); ",[38,489,490],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F [ 1, 2, 3 ] — convert each item to a number\n",[38,492,493,495,498,500,503,506,509,512,515,518,520,522,525,528,531],{"class":40,"line":280},[38,494,45],{"class":44},[38,496,497],{"class":48}," total",[38,499,52],{"class":44},[38,501,502],{"class":59}," c.",[38,504,505],{"class":118},"reduce",[38,507,508],{"class":59},"((",[38,510,511],{"class":267},"acc",[38,513,514],{"class":59},", ",[38,516,517],{"class":267},"cur",[38,519,271],{"class":59},[38,521,274],{"class":44},[38,523,524],{"class":59}," acc ",[38,526,527],{"class":44},"+",[38,529,530],{"class":59}," cur); ",[38,532,533],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F 6 — add them up with reduce\n",[17,535,536],{},"This gives us the answer we want, but it does have some downsides. For instance, what if the string looked like this:",[28,538,540],{"className":30,"code":539,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"const a = '2 + (2 * 2)';\n",[35,541,542],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,543,544,546,548,550,553],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,545,45],{"class":44},[38,547,49],{"class":48},[38,549,52],{"class":44},[38,551,552],{"class":55}," '2 + (2 * 2)'",[38,554,60],{"class":59},[17,556,557,558,560],{},"Then splitting on ",[35,559,527],{}," gives you:",[28,562,564],{"className":30,"code":563,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"const b = a.split(' + '); \u002F\u002F [ \"2\", \"(2 * 2)\" ]\n",[35,565,566],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,567,568,570,572,574,576,578,580,582,584],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,569,45],{"class":44},[38,571,451],{"class":48},[38,573,52],{"class":44},[38,575,456],{"class":59},[38,577,459],{"class":118},[38,579,292],{"class":59},[38,581,464],{"class":55},[38,583,467],{"class":59},[38,585,586],{"class":124},"\u002F\u002F [ \"2\", \"(2 * 2)\" ]\n",[17,588,589],{},"And that breaks. So this approach really only works for simple calculations. For anything more complex, it's not the right tool.",[12,591,593],{"id":592},"references","References",[595,596,597,604],"ul",{},[598,599,600],"li",{},[66,601,603],{"href":134,"rel":602},[136],"MDN - eval",[598,605,606],{},[66,607,609],{"href":156,"rel":608},[136],"ESLint no-eval",[611,612,613],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}html pre.shiki code .s_sBn, html code.shiki .s_sBn{--shiki-default:#FFB757}",{"title":33,"searchDepth":108,"depth":108,"links":615},[616,617,618,623],{"id":14,"depth":108,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":108,"text":23},{"id":74,"depth":108,"text":75,"children":619},[620,621,622],{"id":82,"depth":115,"text":82},{"id":217,"depth":115,"text":218},{"id":419,"depth":115,"text":420},{"id":592,"depth":108,"text":593},"JavaScript","2023-03-21 14:56:38","I came across a fun little JavaScript puzzle the other day, so I jotted down my thought process as a quick post — maybe one day I'll come back and read it myself. The challenge: take a math expression stored as a string and compute its result, but you're not allowed to use eval. We'll look at why eval is a bad idea, and a couple of safer ways to solve it.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fjavascript-puzzle-01-evaluate-string-without-eval","3",{"title":6,"description":626},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-puzzle-01-evaluate-string-without-eval",[624,636,82],"Puzzle",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F21\u002Fjavascript-puzzle-01-evaluate-string-without-eval\u002F","aBU8fxanwvFXCssxIGt0fm4of82sgKre0tKW63IKPnE",{"newer":641,"older":645},{"url":642,"title":643,"date":644},"\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F30\u002Fimporting-images-in-vue\u002F","How to Import Images in Vue (Vue CLI and Vite)","2023-03-30 21:19:00",{"url":646,"title":647,"date":648},"\u002Fen\u002Flearning\u002F2023\u002F03\u002F15\u002Fwill-chatgpt-ai-replace-engineers\u002F","About Whether ChatGPT \u002F AI Will Replace Engineers","2023-03-15 10:33:02",[650,655,660],{"url":651,"title":652,"date":653,"readingMinutes":654},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F10\u002Fweb-crypto-api-encryption-guide\u002F","No crypto Package, No Node.js — The Web Crypto API Does It All in the Browser","2026-03-10 09:45:08","9",{"url":656,"title":657,"date":658,"readingMinutes":659},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fjquery-why-it-declined\u002F","jQuery Was Once King — So Why Did It Fall Off?","2025-12-08 21:35:24","7",{"url":661,"title":662,"date":663,"readingMinutes":664},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-generator-functions\u002F","What Are JavaScript Generator Functions (function*)? The Function You Can Pause and Resume","2025-12-05 13:40:31","5",1784013062825]